olive oil
2 potatoes
1 tin sweetcorn
1 packet garlic paste
20 g butter
1 sachet Chicken-Style Stock Powder
1 packet pork schnitzels
1 tbs plain flour
1 packet panko breadcrumbs
1 egg
1 stalk celery
1 bag Slaw Mix
1 packet garlic aioli
1 bag parsley
1 sachet Tex-Mex spice blend

• Boil the kettle. Half-fill a medium saucepan with boiling water, then add a generous pinch of salt.
• Cut potato into large chunks. Drain the sweetcorn.
• Cook potato in boiling water, over high heat, until easily pierced with a fork, 12-15 minutes. Drain.
• Return saucepan to medium-high heat, add garlic paste and the butter and cook, stirring, until fragrant, 1 minute.
• Add chicken-style stock powder. Stir to combine, then remove from heat.
• Add potato and corn to the pan and toss to coat. Lightly crush with a fork. Cover to keep warm.

TIP: Add a splash of water if the potato looks dry!

• Meanwhile, separate pork (if stuck together) to get two per person.
• In a shallow bowl, combine the plain flour and a pinch of salt. In a second shallow bowl, whisk the egg. In a third shallow bowl, place panko breadcrumbs and Tex-Mex spice blend.
• Coat pork first in the flour, followed by the egg and finally, the breadcrumbs. Set aside on a plate.

Little cooks: Help crumb the pork! Use one hand for the wet ingredients and the other for the dry ingredients to avoid sticky fingers.

• Heat a large frying pan over medium-high with enough olive oil to coat the base.
• When oil is hot, cook pork schnitzels in batches until golden and cooked through, 1-2 minutes each side. Transfer to a paper towel-lined plate.

• Thinly slice celery.
• In a medium bowl, combine slaw mix, celery and garlic aioli. Season to taste.
• Divide Tex-Mex crumbed pork, crushed sweetcorn potatoes and aioli slaw between plates.
• Tear over parsley to serve. Enjoy!